{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658402"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:47:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20748"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20748"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97037"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13624"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11717"},{"type":"tags","id":"12613"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32763"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97037"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMumps is a viral infection primarily affecting the salivary glands. While parotitis is the characteristic presentation, the virus can affect multiple organ systems.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common extrasalivary gland complication of mumps?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Encephalitis","Orchitis","Pancreatitis","Aseptic meningitis","Oophoritis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAseptic meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common extrasalivary gland complication of mumps, occurring in up to 15% of cases. It typically develops three to 10 days after the onset of parotitis, though it can occasionally precede or occur without parotid involvement. The clinical presentation includes headache, fever, neck stiffness, and photophobia. Cerebrospinal fluid analysis typically shows lymphocytic pleocytosis with normal glucose and elevated protein levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other complications of mumps include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrchitis\u003C/strong\u003E (inflammation of the testes) occurs in approximately 20-30% of post-pubertal males with mumps, but is less common overall than meningitis when considering the entire population affected by mumps\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an uncommon complication occurring in about 4% of mumps cases\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOophoritis\u003C/strong\u003E (inflammation of the ovaries) is a rare complication affecting approximately 5% of post-pubertal females with mumps\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEncephalitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious complication of mumps, occurring in less than 1% of cases\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost cases of mumps meningitis resolve without permanent neurological sequelae, though the recovery period may last several weeks. The MMR vaccine has significantly reduced the incidence of mumps and its complications in countries with high vaccination coverage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aseptic meningitis is the most common extrasalivary gland complication of mumps, occurring in up to 15% of cases.","Mumps virus can spread to the central nervous system via haematogenous route.","Most cases of mumps meningitis resolve without permanent neurological sequelae."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 350-351."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20748"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79653"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T06:30:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T06:31:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13624"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97037"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11717"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Viral infections","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-08T11:34:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-08T11:34:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12613"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Mumps","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-28T20:33:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-28T20:33:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"da